# Theme override rules

## Theme strategy

- The base Shower theme is the foundation and should not be rewritten without explicit user request.
- Prefer additive styling on top of the existing theme.
- Treat this stylesheet as a layer of overrides and presentation-specific components.

## Visual consistency priorities

- Prioritize consistency of colors, spacing, and composition.
- When unsure, preserve the existing visual rhythm instead of introducing a new one.
- Keep slide templates visually related to each other.

## CSS editing discipline

- Prefer extending existing project classes over rewriting base theme selectors.
- Avoid broad selectors that may unexpectedly affect many slides.
- Make the smallest CSS change that achieves the requested result.
- Do not change HTML structure only to make CSS easier unless approved.

## New classes

- Reuse existing classes first.
- Create a new class only if:
  - existing classes are not enough; and
  - the class is likely reusable.
- Avoid one-off styling classes for tiny local fixes.

## Images and layout

- When styling slides with images, preserve the current template unless the user explicitly asks for a different template.
- Do not turn a centered-image slide into a fullscreen-image slide without approval.
- Do not let image styling silently redefine spacing rules for other slides.
